permission and ownership 
each file has perrmissions on who can own it and who can run execute and change it 
chown newuser filename -> changes file ownder to the  new user
chgrp group filename -> change file owner to new group 
chown user:newgroup filename -> changes owner and group 
7 -> read write and execute    first number (user)
6 -> read and write            second number (group) 
5 -> read and execute          third number ( otheres ) 
4 -> read                   
0 -> no permissions 
chmod (number ) filename -> changes permission of which user group or others can run read or write in it 
ls -l -> can view permissions of all the files you have 
./file -> run file 
#!/bin/bash -> makes sure to  turn file into a script 

